# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-series-arima
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Different fields of study define autocorrelation differently, and not all of these definitions are equivalent.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In some fields, the term is used interchangeably with autocovariance.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Various time series models incorporate autocorrelation, such as unit root processes, trend-stationary processes, autoregressive processes, and moving average processes.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In statistics, the autocorrelation of a real or complex random process is the Pearson correlation between values of the process at different times, as a function of the two times or of the time lag.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Let $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ be a random process over time and $X_{t}$ be the random variable at time t .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator and the bar represents complex conjugation.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Note that the expectation may not be well defined.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Suppose that the process has mean $\mu _{t}$ and variance $\sigma _{t}^{2}$ at time t , for each t .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Note that this expression is not well defined for all-time series or processes, because the mean may not exist, or the variance may be zero (for a constant process) or infinite (for processes with distribution lacking well-behaved moments, such as certain types of power law).
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] This further implies that the autocovariance and autocorrelation can be expressed as a function of the time-lag, and that this would be an even function of the lag $\tau =t_{2}-t_{1}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] It is common practice in some disciplines (e.g. statistics and time series analysis) to normalize the autocovariance function to get a time-dependent Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] However, in other disciplines (e.g. engineering) the normalization is usually dropped and the terms "autocorrelation" and "autocovariance" are used interchangeably.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] If the function $\rho _{XX}$ is well defined, its value must lie in the range $[-1,1]$ , with 1 indicating perfect correlation and −1 indicating perfect anti-correlation.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The normalization is important both because the interpretation of the autocorrelation as a correlation provides a scale-free measure of the strength of statistical dependence, and because the normalization has an effect on the statistical properties of the estimated autocorrelations.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] For a WSS process: $\left|\operatorname {R} _{XX}(\tau )\right|\leq \operatorname {R} _{XX}(0)$ Notice that $\operatorname {R} _{XX}(0)$ is always real.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The autocorrelation of a continuous-time white noise signal will have a strong peak (represented by a Dirac delta function) at $\tau =0$ and will be exactly 0 for all other $\tau$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The autocorrelation matrix is used in various digital signal processing algorithms.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] where ${}^{\rm {T}}$ denotes transposition of the vector.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Here ${}^{\rm {H}}$ denotes Hermitian transpose.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In signal processing, the above definition is often used without the normalization, that is, without subtracting the mean and dividing by the variance.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] When the autocorrelation function is normalized by mean and variance, it is sometimes referred to as the **autocorrelation coefficient** or autocovariance function.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Given a signal $f(t)$ , the continuous autocorrelation $R_{ff}(\tau )$ is most often defined as the continuous cross-correlation integral of $f(t)$ with itself, at lag $\tau$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] where ${\overline {f(t)}}$ represents the complex conjugate of $f(t)$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Note that the parameter t in the integral is a dummy variable and is only necessary to calculate the integral.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The above definitions work for signals that are square integrable, or square summable, that is, of finite energy.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Signals that "last forever" are treated instead as random processes, in which case different definitions are needed, based on expected values.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] For processes that are not stationary, these will also be functions of t , or n .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] For processes that are also ergodic, the expectation can be replaced by the limit of a time average.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] These definitions have the advantage that they give sensible well-defined single-parameter results for periodic functions, even when those functions are not the output of stationary ergodic processes.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Alternatively, signals that *last forever* can be treated by a short-time autocorrelation function analysis, using finite time integrals.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In the following, we will describe properties of one-dimensional autocorrelations only, since most properties are easily transferred from the one-dimensional case to the multi-dimensional cases.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] These properties hold for wide-sense stationary processes.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Multi-dimensional autocorrelation is defined similarly.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] When mean values are subtracted from signals before computing an autocorrelation function, the resulting function is usually called an auto-covariance function.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] For data expressed as a discrete sequence, it is frequently necessary to compute the autocorrelation with high computational efficiency.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] A brute force method based on the signal processing definition ${\textstyle R_{xx}(j)=\sum _{n}x_{n}\,{\overline {x}}_{n-j}}$ can be used when the signal size is small.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In this calculation we do not perform the carry-over operation during addition as is usual in normal multiplication.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Note that we can halve the number of operations required by exploiting the inherent symmetry of the autocorrelation.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] While the brute force algorithm is order *n*2, several efficient algorithms exist which can compute the autocorrelation in order *n* log(*n*).
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] where IFFT denotes the inverse fast Fourier transform.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Alternatively, a multiple τ correlation can be performed by using brute force calculation for low τ values, and then progressively binning the *X*(*t*) data with a logarithmic density to compute higher values, resulting in the same *n* log(*n*) efficiency, but with lower memory requirements.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] When the true mean $\mu$ and variance $\sigma ^{2}$ are known, this estimate is **unbiased**.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The advantage of estimates of the last type is that the set of estimated autocorrelations, as a function of k , then form a function which is a valid autocorrelation in the sense that it is possible to define a theoretical process having exactly that autocorrelation.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Other estimates can suffer from the problem that, if they are used to calculate the variance of a linear combination of the X 's, the variance calculated may turn out to be negative.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In time series analysis, the **Hassani −1/2 theorem** is a finite-sample identity concerning the conventional estimator of the *sample autocorrelation function* (ACF).
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The identity follows from the fact that the sample autocovariances are computed after subtracting the sample mean.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Consequently, the centered observations sum to zero, which imposes an algebraic constraint on the full set of sample autocorrelations.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The theorem is therefore a property of the estimator and the finite sample, rather than a property of the underlying stochastic process.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The result implies that sample autocorrelations across lags are not independent.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] It also shows that the sample ACF cannot be positive overall when summed across all positive lags.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] This has led to cautions against interpreting the sum of estimated autocorrelations as a direct measure of total dependence, persistence or long-memory behaviour, since the full-lag sum is fixed at $-1/2$ regardless of the underlying stationary time series.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The theorem has been discussed in relation to diagnostic checking and model selection in time series analysis.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In particular, later work has examined its implications for tests based on sample autocorrelations, including the Ljung–Box statistic, and for the interpretation of empirical ACF patterns in short-memory and long-memory processes.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The identity has also been used to emphasize the distinction between theoretical autocorrelations of a process and empirical autocorrelations estimated from a finite sample.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The theorem applies to the standard sample-mean-corrected ACF estimator.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] It should not be confused with statements about the sum of the theoretical autocorrelation function of the underlying process, which may vary depending on the model and its parameters.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] With multiple interrelated data series, vector autoregression (VAR) or its extensions are used.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In ordinary least squares (OLS), the adequacy of a model specification can be checked in part by establishing whether there is autocorrelation of the regression residuals.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Problematic autocorrelation of the errors, which themselves are unobserved, can generally be detected because it produces autocorrelation in the observable residuals.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] While it does not bias the OLS coefficient estimates, the standard errors tend to be underestimated (and the t-scores overestimated) when the autocorrelations of the errors at low lags are positive.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The traditional test for the presence of first-order autocorrelation is the Durbin–Watson statistic or, if the explanatory variables include a lagged dependent variable, Durbin's h statistic.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The Durbin-Watson can be linearly mapped however to the Pearson correlation between values and their lags.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] A more flexible test, covering autocorrelation of higher orders and applicable whether or not the regressors include lags of the dependent variable, is the Breusch–Godfrey test.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] This involves an auxiliary regression, wherein the residuals obtained from estimating the model of interest are regressed on (a) the original regressors and (b) *k* lags of the residuals, where 'k' is the order of the test.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] The simplest version of the test statistic from this auxiliary regression is *TR*2, where *T* is the sample size and *R*2 is the coefficient of determination.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Under the null hypothesis of no autocorrelation, this statistic is asymptotically distributed as $\chi ^{2}$ with *k* degrees of freedom.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] Responses to nonzero autocorrelation include generalized least squares and the Newey–West HAC estimator (Heteroskedasticity and Autocorrelation Consistent).
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] In the estimation of a moving average model (MA), the autocorrelation function is used to determine the appropriate number of lagged error terms to be included.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] This is based on the fact that for an MA process of order *q*, we have $R(\tau )\neq 0$ , for $\tau =0,1,\ldots ,q$ , and $R(\tau )=0$ , for $\tau >q$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] A time series of a random variable has serial dependence if the value at some time t in the series is statistically dependent on the value at another time s .
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] A series is serially independent if there is no dependence between any pair.
[src:time-series-arima/autocorrelation] If a time series $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is stationary, then statistical dependence between the pair $(X_{t},X_{s})$ would imply that there is statistical dependence between all pairs of values at the same lag $\tau =s-t$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In time series analysis used in statistics and econometrics, **autoregressive integrated moving average** (**ARIMA**) and **seasonal ARIMA** (**SARIMA**) models are generalizations of the autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model to non-stationary series and periodic variation, respectively.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] All these models are fitted to time series in order to better understand it and predict future values.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The purpose of these generalizations is to fit the data as well as possible.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, ARMA assumes that the series is stationary, that is, its expected value is constant in time.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If instead the series has a trend (but a constant variance/autocovariance), the trend is removed by "differencing", leaving a stationary series.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This operation generalizes ARMA and corresponds to the "integrated" part of ARIMA.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Analogously, periodic variation is removed by "seasonal differencing".
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] As in ARMA, the "autoregressive" (AR) part of ARIMA indicates that the evolving variable of interest is regressed on its prior values.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "moving average" (MA) part indicates that the regression error is a linear combination of error terms whose values occurred contemporaneously and at various times in the past.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The "integrated" (I) part indicates that the data values have been replaced with the difference between each value and the previous value.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] According to Wold's decomposition theorem the ARMA model is sufficient to describe a **regular** (a.k.a. purely nondeterministic) wide-sense stationary time series.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] This motivates to make such a non-stationary time series stationary, e.g., by using differencing, before using ARMA.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time series contains a **predictable** sub-process (a.k.a. pure sine or complex-valued exponential process), the predictable component is treated as a non-zero-mean but periodic (i.e., seasonal) component in the ARIMA framework that it is eliminated by the seasonal differencing.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal ARIMA models are usually denoted by ARIMA(*p*, *d*, *q*)(*P*, *D*, *Q*)*m*, where the uppercase *P*, *D*, *Q* are the autoregressive, differencing, and moving average terms for the seasonal part of the ARIMA model, and *m* is the number of periods in each season.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] When two of the parameters are 0, the model may be referred to based on the non-zero parameter, dropping "AR", "I" or "MA" from the acronym.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where L is the lag operator, the $\alpha _{i}$ are the parameters of the autoregressive part of the model, the $\theta _{i}$ are the parameters of the moving average part and the $\varepsilon _{t}$ are error terms.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The error terms $\varepsilon _{t}$ are generally assumed to be independent, identically distributed variables sampled from a normal distribution with zero mean.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] and so is special case of an ARMA(*p+d*, *q*) process having the autoregressive polynomial with *d* unit roots.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The above can be generalized as follows.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The explicit identification of the factorization of the autoregression polynomial into factors as above can be extended to other cases, firstly to apply to the moving average polynomial and secondly to include other special factors.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For example, having a factor $(1-L^{s})$ in a model is one way of including a non-stationary seasonality of period *s* into the model; this factor has the effect of re-expressing the data as changes from *s* periods ago.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Another example is the factor $\left(1-{\sqrt {3}}L+L^{2}\right)$ , which includes a (non-stationary) seasonality of period 2.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The effect of the first type of factor is to allow each season's value to drift separately over time, whereas with the second type values for adjacent seasons move together.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A stationary time series's properties do not change.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Specifically, for a wide-sense stationary time series, the mean and the variance/autocovariance are constant over time.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] **Differencing** in statistics is a transformation applied to a non-stationary time-series in order to make it trend stationary (i.e., stationary *in the mean sense*), by removing or subtracting the trend or non-constant mean.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] However, it does not affect the non-stationarity of the variance or autocovariance.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Likewise, *seasonal differencing* or *deseasonalization* is applied to a time-series to remove the seasonal component.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] From the perspective of signal processing, especially the Fourier spectral analysis theory, the trend is a low-frequency part in the spectrum of a series, while the season is a periodic-frequency part.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Therefore, differencing is a high-pass (that is, low-stop) filter and the seasonal-differencing is a comb filter to suppress respectively the low-frequency trend and the periodic-frequency season in the spectrum domain (rather than directly in the time domain).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To difference the data, we compute the difference between consecutive observations.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Seasonal differencing involves computing the difference between an observation and the corresponding observation in the previous season e.g a year.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The differenced data are then used for the estimation of an ARMA model.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Some well-known special cases arise naturally or are mathematically equivalent to other popular forecasting models.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The order *p* and *q* can be determined using the sample autocorrelation function (ACF), partial autocorrelation function (PACF), and/or extended autocorrelation function (EACF) method.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Other alternative methods include AIC, BIC, etc.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] To determine the order of a non-seasonal ARIMA model, a useful criterion is the Akaike information criterion (AIC).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] where *L*is the likelihood of the data, *p*is the order of the autoregressive part and *q*is the order of the moving average part.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The *k* represents the intercept of the ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For AIC, if *k* = 1 then there is an intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*≠ 0) and if *k*= 0 then there is no intercept in the ARIMA model (*c*= 0).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The objective is to minimize the AIC, AICc or BIC values for a good model.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The lower the value of one of these criteria for a range of models being investigated, the better the model will suit the data.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The AIC and the BIC are used for two completely different purposes.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] While the AIC tries to approximate models towards the reality of the situation, the BIC attempts to find the perfect fit.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The BIC approach is often criticized as there never is a perfect fit to real-life complex data; however, it is still a useful method for selection as it penalizes models more heavily for having more parameters than the AIC would.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] AICc can only be used to compare ARIMA models with the same orders of differencing.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For ARIMAs with different orders of differencing, RMSE can be used for model comparison.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The ARIMA model can be viewed as a "cascade" of two models.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Now forecasts can be made for the process $Y_{t}$ , using a generalization of the method of autoregressive forecasting.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] The forecast intervals (confidence intervals for forecasts) for ARIMA models are based on assumptions that the residuals are uncorrelated and normally distributed.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If either of these assumptions does not hold, then the forecast intervals may be incorrect.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For this reason, researchers plot the ACF and histogram of the residuals to check the assumptions before producing forecast intervals.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] For $h=1$ , $v_{T+h\,\mid \,T}={\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ for all ARIMA models regardless of parameters and orders.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] In general, forecast intervals from ARIMA models will increase as the forecast horizon increases.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] A number of variations on the ARIMA model are commonly employed.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If multiple time series are used then the $X_{t}$ can be thought of as vectors and a VARIMA model may be appropriate.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Sometimes a seasonal effect is suspected in the model; in that case, it is generally considered better to use a SARIMA (seasonal ARIMA) model than to increase the order of the AR or MA parts of the model.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] If the time-series is suspected to exhibit long-range dependence, then the *d* parameter may be allowed to have non-integer values in an autoregressive fractionally integrated moving average model, which is also called a Fractional ARIMA (FARIMA or ARFIMA) model.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-integrated-moving-average] Various packages that apply methodology like Box–Jenkins parameter optimization are available to find the right parameters for the ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] In statistics, an **autoregressive** (**AR**) **model** is a modelled representation of a type of random process.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] It can be used to describe time-varying processes from many natural and artificial sources.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The model specifies output variables that are dependent linearly on their own previous values on a stochastic basis.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The model is in the form of a stochastic difference equation (or recurrence relation) which should not be confused with a differential equation.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Another important extension is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, where the autoregressive coefficients are allowed to change over time to model evolving or non-stationary processes.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] TVAR models are widely applied in cases where the underlying dynamics of the system are not constant, such as in sensors time series modelling, climate science, economics and finance (as econometrics), signal processing, telecommunications, radar systems, and biological signals.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Unlike the moving-average (MA) model, the autoregressive model is not always stationary; non-stationarity can arise either due to the presence of a unit root or due to time-varying model parameters, as in time-varying autoregressive models.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Large language models are called autoregressive, but they are not a classical autoregressive model in this sense because they are not linear.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The notation $AR(p)$ indicates an autoregressive model of order *p*.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] where $\varphi _{1},\ldots ,\varphi _{p}$ are the *parameters* of the model, and $\varepsilon _{t}$ is white noise.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] An autoregressive model can thus be viewed as the output of an all-pole infinite impulse response filter whose input is white noise.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Some parameter constraints are necessary for the model to remain weak-sense stationary.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] For example, processes in the AR(1) model with $|\varphi _{1}|\geq 1$ are not stationary.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] More generally, for an AR(*p*) model to be weak-sense stationary, the roots of the polynomial $\Phi (z):=\textstyle 1-\sum _{i=1}^{p}\varphi _{i}z^{i}$ must lie outside the unit circle, i.e., each (complex) root $z_{i}$ must satisfy $|z_{i}|>1$ (see pages 89,92 ).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] In an AR process, a one-time shock affects values of the evolving variable infinitely far into the future.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] A non-zero value for $\varepsilon _{t}$ at say time *t*=1 affects $X_{1}$ by the amount $\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{2}$ in terms of $X_{1}$ , this affects $X_{2}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{3}$ in terms of $X_{2}$ , this affects $X_{3}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}^{2}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Continuing this process shows that the effect of $\varepsilon _{1}$ never ends, although if the process is stationary then the effect diminishes toward zero in the limit.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Because each shock affects *X* values infinitely far into the future from when they occur, any given value *X**t* is affected by shocks occurring infinitely far into the past.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] When the polynomial division on the right side is carried out, the polynomial in the backshift operator applied to $\varepsilon _{t}$ has an infinite order—that is, an infinite number of lagged values of $\varepsilon _{t}$ appear on the right side of the equation.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] where *B* is the backshift operator, where $\varphi (\cdot )$ is the function defining the autoregression, and where $\varphi _{k}$ are the coefficients in the autoregression.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The formula is valid only if all the roots have multiplicity 1.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process is a sum of decaying exponentials.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The simplest AR process is AR(0), which has no dependence between the terms.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Only the error/innovation/noise term contributes to the output of the process, so in the figure, AR(0) corresponds to white noise.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] For an AR(1) process with a positive $\varphi$ , only the previous term in the process and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi$ is close to 0, then the process still looks like white noise, but as $\varphi$ approaches 1, the output gets a larger contribution from the previous term relative to the noise.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] This results in a "smoothing" or integration of the output, similar to a low pass filter.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] For an AR(2) process, the previous two terms and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] If both $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ are positive, the output will resemble a low pass filter, with the high frequency part of the noise decreased.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi _{1}$ is positive while $\varphi _{2}$ is negative, then the process favors changes in sign between terms of the process.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] This can be linked to edge detection or detection of change in direction.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] An AR(1) process is given by: $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon _{t}\,$ where $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a white noise process with zero mean and constant variance $\sigma _{\varepsilon }^{2}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] (Note: The subscript on $\varphi _{1}$ has been dropped.) The process is weak-sense stationary if $|\varphi |<1$ since it is obtained as the output of a stable filter whose input is white noise.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] where $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of $\varepsilon _{t}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] and then by noticing that the quantity above is a stable fixed point of this relation.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] It can be seen that the autocovariance function decays with a decay time (also called time constant) of $\tau =1/(1-\varphi )$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The spectral density function is the Fourier transform of the autocovariance function.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] This expression is periodic due to the discrete nature of the $X_{j}$ , which is manifested as the cosine term in the denominator.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] where $\gamma =1/\tau$ is the angular frequency associated with the decay time $\tau$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] An alternative expression for $X_{t}$ can be derived by first substituting $\varphi X_{t-2}+\varepsilon _{t-1}$ for $X_{t-1}$ in the defining equation.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] It is seen that $X_{t}$ is white noise convolved with the $\varphi ^{k}$ kernel plus the constant mean.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] If the white noise $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a Gaussian process then $X_{t}$ is also a Gaussian process.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] In other cases, the central limit theorem indicates that $X_{t}$ will be approximately normally distributed when $\varphi$ is close to one.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] For $\varepsilon _{t}=0$ , the process $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}$ will be a geometric progression (*exponential* growth or decay).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] In this case, the solution can be found analytically: $X_{t}=a\varphi ^{t}$ whereby a is an unknown constant (initial condition).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The AR(1) model is the discrete-time analogy of the continuous Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] It is therefore sometimes useful to understand the properties of the AR(1) model cast in an equivalent form.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(p) process equals zero at lags larger than *p*, so the appropriate maximum lag *p* is the one after which the partial autocorrelations are all zero.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] There are many ways to estimate the coefficients, such as the ordinary least squares procedure or method of moments (through Yule–Walker equations).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] It is based on parameters $\varphi _{i}$ where *i* = 1, ..., *p*.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] There is a direct correspondence between these parameters and the covariance function of the process, and this correspondence can be inverted to determine the parameters from the autocorrelation function (which is itself obtained from the covariances).
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] This is done using the Yule–Walker equations.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The Yule–Walker equations, named for Udny Yule and Gilbert Walker, are the following set of equations.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Here $\gamma _{m}$ is the autocovariance function of Xt, $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of the input noise process, and $\delta _{m,0}$ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] An alternative formulation is in terms of the autocorrelation function.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The AR parameters are determined by the first *p*+1 elements $\rho (\tau )$ of the autocorrelation function.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The above equations (the Yule–Walker equations) provide several routes to estimating the parameters of an AR(*p*) model, by replacing the theoretical covariances with estimated values.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] but the reasoning behind this applies to the use of any set of estimated AR parameters.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Compared to the estimation scheme using only the forward prediction equations, different estimates of the autocovariances are produced, and the estimates have different stability properties.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Other possible approaches to estimation include maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Substantial differences in the results of these approaches can occur if the observed series is short, or if the process is close to non-stationarity.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The terms involving square roots are all real in the case of complex poles since they exist only when $\varphi _{2}<0$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The process is non-stationary when the poles are on or outside the unit circle, or equivalently when the characteristic roots are on or inside the unit circle.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The process is stable when the poles are strictly within the unit circle (roots strictly outside the unit circle), or equivalently when the coefficients are in the triangle $-1\leq \varphi _{2}\leq 1-|\varphi _{1}|$ .
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The impulse response of a system is the change in an evolving variable in response to a change in the value of a shock term *k* periods earlier, as a function of *k*.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Since the AR model is a special case of the vector autoregressive model, the computation of the impulse response in vector autoregression#impulse response applies here.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] have been estimated, the autoregression can be used to forecast an arbitrary number of periods into the future.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] The output of the autoregressive equation is the forecast for the first unobserved period.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Then for future periods the same procedure is used, each time using one more forecast value on the right side of the predictive equation until, after *p* predictions, all *p* right-side values are predicted values from preceding steps.
[src:time-series-arima/autoregressive-model] Each of the last three can be quantified and combined to give a confidence interval for the *n*-step-ahead predictions; the confidence interval will become wider as *n* increases because of the use of an increasing number of estimated values for the right-side variables.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] In time series analysis, the **Box–Jenkins method**, named after the statisticians George Box and Gwilym Jenkins, applies autoregressive moving average (ARMA) or autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) models to find the best fit of a time-series model to past values of a time series.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] *Parameter estimation* using computation algorithms to arrive at coefficients that best fit the selected ARIMA model.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The most common methods use maximum likelihood estimation or non-linear least-squares estimation.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] *Statistical model checking* by testing whether the estimated model conforms to the specifications of a stationary univariate process.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] In particular, the residuals should be independent of each other and constant in mean and variance over time.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The data they used were from a gas furnace.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] These data are well known as the Box and Jenkins gas furnace data for benchmarking predictive models.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Commandeur & Koopman (2007, §10.4) argue that the Box–Jenkins approach is fundamentally problematic.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The problem arises because in "the economic and social fields, real series are never stationary however much differencing is done".
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Thus the investigator has to face the question: how close to stationary is close enough?
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] As the authors note, "This is a hard question to answer".
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The authors further argue that rather than using Box–Jenkins, it is better to use state space methods, as stationarity of the time series is then not required.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The first step in developing a Box–Jenkins model is to determine whether the time series is stationary.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] In particular, it is necessary to check whether there is significant seasonality that needs to be modelled.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Stationarity can be assessed from a run sequence plot.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The run sequence plot should show constant location and scale, suggesting that mean and variance of the time series are constant.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Furthermore, non-stationarity can also be detected from an autocorrelation plot with a very slow decay.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] One can also utilize a Dickey-Fuller test or Augmented Dickey-Fuller test.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Seasonality (or periodicity) can usually be assessed from an autocorrelation plot, a seasonal subseries plot, or a spectral plot.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Box and Jenkins recommend the differencing approach to achieve stationarity.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] However, fitting a curve and subtracting the fitted values from the original data can also be used in the context of Box–Jenkins models.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] At the model identification stage, the goal is to detect seasonality, if it exists, and to identify the order for the seasonal autoregressive and seasonal moving average terms.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] For many series, the period is known and a single seasonality term is sufficient.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] For example, for monthly data one would typically include either a seasonal AR 12 term or a seasonal MA 12 term.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] For Box–Jenkins models, one does not explicitly remove seasonality before fitting the model.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Instead, one includes the order of the seasonal terms in the model specification to the ARIMA estimation software.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] However, it may be helpful to apply a seasonal difference to the data and regenerate the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation plots.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] This may help in the model identification of the non-seasonal component of the model.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] In some cases, the seasonal differencing may remove most or all of the seasonality effect.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Once stationarity and seasonality have been addressed, the next step is to identify the order (i.e. the *p* and *q*) of the autoregressive and moving average terms.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Different authors have different approaches for identifying *p* and *q*.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Brockwell and Davis (1991) state "our prime criterion for model selection [among ARMA(p,q) models] will be the AICc", i.e. the Akaike information criterion with correction.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Other authors use the autocorrelation plot and the partial autocorrelation plot, described below.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The sample autocorrelation plot and the sample partial autocorrelation plot are compared to the theoretical behavior of these plots when the order is known.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Specifically, for an AR(1) process, the sample autocorrelation function should have an exponentially decreasing appearance.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] However, higher-order AR processes are often a mixture of exponentially decreasing and damped sinusoidal components.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] For higher-order autoregressive processes, the sample autocorrelation needs to be supplemented with a partial autocorrelation plot.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(*p*) process becomes zero at lag *p* + 1 and greater, so we examine the sample partial autocorrelation function to see if there is evidence of a departure from zero.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] This is usually determined by placing a 95% confidence interval on the sample partial autocorrelation plot (most software programs that generate sample autocorrelation plots also plot this confidence interval).
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] If the software program does not generate the confidence band, it is approximately $\pm 2/{\sqrt {N}}$ , with *N* denoting the sample size.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The autocorrelation function of a MA(*q*) process becomes zero at lag *q* + 1 and greater, so we examine the sample autocorrelation function to see where it essentially becomes zero.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] We do this by placing the 95% confidence interval for the sample autocorrelation function on the sample autocorrelation plot.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Most software that can generate the autocorrelation plot can also generate this confidence interval.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The sample partial autocorrelation function is generally not helpful for identifying the order of the moving average process.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The following table summarizes how one can use the sample autocorrelation function for model identification.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] In practice, the sample autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation functions are random variables and do not give the same picture as the theoretical functions.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] This makes the model identification more difficult.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] In particular, mixed models can be particularly difficult to identify.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Although experience is helpful, developing good models using these sample plots can involve much trial and error.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Estimating the parameters for Box–Jenkins models involves numerically approximating the solutions of nonlinear equations.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] For this reason, it is common to use statistical software designed to handle to the approach – virtually all modern statistical packages feature this capability.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The main approaches to fitting Box–Jenkins models are nonlinear least squares and maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Maximum likelihood estimation is generally the preferred technique.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The likelihood equations for the full Box–Jenkins model are complicated and are not included here.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] See (Brockwell and Davis, 1991) for the mathematical details.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Model diagnostics for Box–Jenkins models is similar to model validation for non-linear least squares fitting.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] That is, the error term *At* is assumed to follow the assumptions for a stationary univariate process.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] The residuals should be white noise (or independent when their distributions are normal) drawings from a fixed distribution with a constant mean and variance.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] If the Box–Jenkins model is a good model for the data, the residuals should satisfy these assumptions.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] If these assumptions are not satisfied, one needs to fit a more appropriate model.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] That is, go back to the model identification step and try to develop a better model.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] Hopefully the analysis of the residuals can provide some clues as to a more appropriate model.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] One way to assess if the residuals from the Box–Jenkins model follow the assumptions is to generate statistical graphics (including an autocorrelation plot) of the residuals.
[src:time-series-arima/box-jenkins-method] One could also look at the value of the Box–Ljung statistic.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] In time series analysis, the **moving-average model** (**MA model**), also called the **moving-average process**, is a standard approach for modeling univariate time series.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] An MA model expresses the current value of a time series as a linear function of current and past random shocks (error terms) with finite lag length.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] In contrast to an autoregressive model, which regresses the variable on its past values, the moving-average model relies solely on the dependency structure of the error terms.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Together with the autoregressive (AR) model, the moving-average model is a special case and key component of the more general ARMA and ARIMA models of time series, which have a more complicated stochastic structure.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Contrary to the AR model, the finite MA model is always stationary.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] The moving-average model should not be confused with the moving average, a distinct concept despite some similarities.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] where $\mu$ is the mean of the series, the $\theta _{1},...,\theta _{q}$ are the coefficients of the model and $\varepsilon _{t},\varepsilon _{t-1},...,\varepsilon _{t-q}$ are the error terms.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] The value of *q* is called the order of the MA model.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Thus, a moving-average model is conceptually a linear regression of the current value of the series against current and previous (observed) white noise error terms or random shocks.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] The random shocks at each point are assumed to be mutually independent and to come from the same distribution, typically a normal distribution, with location at zero and constant scale.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] The moving-average model is essentially a finite impulse response filter applied to white noise, with some additional interpretation placed on it.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] The role of the random shocks in the MA model differs from their role in the autoregressive (AR) model in two ways.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] First, they are propagated to future values of the time series directly: for example, $\varepsilon _{t-1}$ appears directly on the right side of the equation for $X_{t}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Fitting a moving-average model is generally more complicated than fitting an autoregressive model.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] This is because the lagged error terms are not observable.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] This means that iterative non-linear fitting procedures need to be used in place of linear least squares.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Moving average models are linear combinations of past white noise terms, while autoregressive models are linear combinations of past time series values.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] ARMA models are more complicated than pure AR and MA models, as they combine both autoregressive and moving average components.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] The autocorrelation function (ACF) of an MA(*q*) process is zero at lag *q* + 1 and greater.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Therefore, we determine the appropriate maximum lag for the estimation by examining the sample autocorrelation function to see where it becomes insignificantly different from zero for all lags beyond a certain lag, which is designated as the maximum lag *q*.
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Sometimes the ACF and partial autocorrelation function (PACF) will suggest that an MA model would be a better model choice and sometimes both AR and MA terms should be used in the same model (see Box–Jenkins method).
[src:time-series-arima/moving-average-model] Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) models are an alternative to segmented regression that can also be used for fitting a moving-average model.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] In time series analysis, the **partial autocorrelation function** (**PACF**) gives the partial correlation of a stationary time series with its own lagged values, regressed the values of the time series at all shorter lags.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] It contrasts with the autocorrelation function, which does not control for other lags.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] This function plays an important role in data analysis aimed at identifying the extent of the lag in an autoregressive (AR) model.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] The use of this function was introduced as part of the Box–Jenkins approach to time series modelling, whereby plotting the partial autocorrelative functions one could determine the appropriate lags **p** in an AR (**p**) model or in an extended ARIMA (**p**,**d**,**q**) model.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] Given a time series $z_{t}$ , the partial autocorrelation of lag k , denoted $\phi _{k,k}$ , is the autocorrelation between $z_{t}$ and $z_{t+k}$ with the linear dependence of $z_{t}$ on $z_{t+1}$ through $z_{t+k-1}$ removed.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] The formula above can be used with sample autocorrelations to find the sample partial autocorrelation function of any given time series.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] The behavior of the partial autocorrelation function mirrors that of the autocorrelation function for autoregressive and moving-average models.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] For example, the partial autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) series cuts off after lag *p* similar to the autocorrelation function of an MA(*q*) series with lag *q*.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] In addition, the autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process tails off just like the partial autocorrelation function of an MA(*q*) process.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] Partial autocorrelation is a commonly used tool for identifying the order of an autoregressive model.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] As previously mentioned, the partial autocorrelation of an AR(*p*) process is zero at lags greater than *p*.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] If an AR model is determined to be appropriate, then the sample partial autocorrelation plot is examined to help identify the order.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] The partial autocorrelation of lags greater than *p* for an AR(*p*) time series are approximately independent and normal with a mean of 0.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] Therefore, a confidence interval can be constructed by dividing a selected z-score by ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] Lags with partial autocorrelations outside of the confidence interval indicate that the AR model's order is likely greater than or equal to the lag.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] Plotting the partial autocorrelation function and drawing the lines of the confidence interval is a common way to analyze the order of an AR model.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] To evaluate the order, one examines the plot to find the lag after which the partial autocorrelations are all within the confidence interval.
[src:time-series-arima/partial-autocorrelation-function] This lag is determined to likely be the AR model's order.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] In mathematics and statistics, a **stationary process** (also called a **strict/strictly stationary process** or **strong/strongly stationary process**) is a stochastic process whose statistical properties, such as mean and variance, do not change over time.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] More formally, the joint probability distribution of the process remains the same when shifted in time.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] This implies that the process is statistically consistent across different time periods.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Because many statistical procedures in time series analysis assume stationarity, non-stationary data are frequently transformed to achieve stationarity before analysis.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] A common cause of non-stationarity is a trend in the mean, which can be due to either a unit root or a deterministic trend.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] In the case of a unit root, stochastic shocks have permanent effects, and the process is not mean-reverting.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] With a deterministic trend, the process is called trend-stationary, and shocks have only transitory effects, with the variable tending towards a deterministically evolving mean.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] A trend-stationary process is not strictly stationary but can be made stationary by removing the trend.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Similarly, processes with unit roots can be made stationary through differencing.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Another type of non-stationary process, distinct from those with trends, is a cyclostationary process, which exhibits cyclical variations over time.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Strict stationarity, as defined above, can be too restrictive for many applications.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Therefore, other forms of stationarity, such as **wide-sense stationarity** or **⁠ N ⁠th-order stationarity**, are often used.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The definitions for different kinds of stationarity are not consistent among different authors (see Other terminology).
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Since $\tau$ does not affect ⁠ $F_{X}(\cdot )$ ⁠, $F_{X}$ is independent of time.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] White noise is the simplest example of a stationary process.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] An example of a discrete-time stationary process where the sample space is also discrete (so that the random variable may take one of ⁠ N ⁠ possible values) is a Bernoulli scheme.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Other examples of a discrete-time stationary process with continuous sample space include some autoregressive and moving average processes that are both subsets of the autoregressive moving average model.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Models with a non-trivial autoregressive component may be either stationary or non-stationary, depending on the parameter values, and important non-stationary special cases are where unit roots exist in the model.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Then $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is a stationary time series, for which realisations consist of a series of constant values, with a different constant value for each realisation.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] A law of large numbers does not apply on this case, as the limiting value of an average from a single realisation takes the random value determined by ⁠ Y ⁠, rather than taking the expected value of ⁠ Y ⁠.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The time average of $X_{t}$ does not converge since the process is not ergodic.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Then $\left\{X_{t}\right\}$ is strictly stationary since (⁠ $(t+Y)$ ⁠ modulo ⁠ $2\pi$ ⁠) follows the same uniform distribution as Y for any ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Keep in mind that a weakly white noise is not necessarily strictly stationary.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] So $\{z_{t}\}$ is a white noise in the weak sense (the mean and cross-covariances are zero, and the variances are all the same), however it is not strictly stationary.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] In **Eq.1**, the distribution of n samples of the stochastic process must be equal to the distribution of the samples shifted in time *for all* ⁠ n ⁠. ⁠ N ⁠th-order stationarity is a weaker form of stationarity where this is only requested for all n up to a certain order ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] A weaker form of stationarity commonly employed in signal processing is known as **weak-sense stationarity**, **wide-sense stationarity (WSS)**, or **covariance stationarity**.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] WSS random processes only require that 1st moment (i.e. the mean) and autocovariance do not vary with respect to time and that the 2nd moment is finite for all times.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Any strictly stationary process that has a finite mean and covariance is also WSS.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The first property implies that the mean function $m_{X}(t)$ must be constant.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The second property implies that the autocovariance function depends only on the *difference* between $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ and only needs to be indexed by one variable rather than two variables.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The third property says that the second moments must be finite for any time ⁠ t ⁠.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The main advantage of wide-sense stationarity is that it places the time-series in the context of Hilbert spaces.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Let ⁠ H ⁠ be the Hilbert space generated by ⁠ $\{x(t)\}$ ⁠ (that is, the closure of the set of all linear combinations of these random variables in the Hilbert space of all square-integrable random variables on the given probability space).
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] By the positive definiteness of the autocovariance function, it follows from Bochner's theorem that there exists a positive measure $\mu$ on the real line such that ⁠ H ⁠ is isomorphic to the Hilbert subspace of ⁠ $L^{2}(\mu )$ ⁠ generated by ⁠ $\{e^{-2\pi i\xi \cdot t}\}$ ⁠.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] where the integral on the right-hand side is interpreted in a suitable (Riemann) sense.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The same result holds for a discrete-time stationary process, with the spectral measure now defined on the unit circle.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] When processing WSS random signals with linear, time-invariant (LTI) filters, it is helpful to think of the correlation function as a linear operator.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Since it is a circulant operator (depends only on the difference between the two arguments), its eigenfunctions are the Fourier complex exponentials.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Additionally, since the eigenfunctions of LTI operators are also complex exponentials, LTI processing of WSS random signals is highly tractable—all computations can be performed in the frequency domain.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Thus, the WSS assumption is widely employed in signal processing algorithms.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The concept of stationarity may be extended to two stochastic processes.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The terminology used for types of stationarity other than strict stationarity can be rather mixed.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] In time series analysis and stochastic processes, stationarizing a time series is a crucial preprocessing step aimed at transforming a non-stationary process into a stationary one.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Several techniques exist for achieving this, depending on the type and order of non-stationarity present.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] For first-order non-stationarity, where the mean of the process varies over time, differencing is a common and effective method: it transforms the series by subtracting each value from its predecessor, thus stabilizing the mean.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] For non-stationarities up to the second order, time-frequency analysis (e.g., Wavelet transform, Wigner distribution function, or Short-time Fourier transform) can be employed to isolate and suppress time-localized, nonstationary spectral components.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Additionally, surrogate data methods can be used to construct strictly stationary versions of the original time series.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] One of the ways for identifying non-stationary times series is the ACF plot.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Sometimes, patterns will be more visible in the ACF plot than in the original time series; however, this is not always the case.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The choice of method for time series stationarization depends on the nature of the non-stationarity and the goals of the analysis, especially when building models that require strict stationarity assumptions, such as ARMA or spectral-based techniques.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] More details on some time series stationarization methods are presented below.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] One way to make some time series first-order stationary is to compute the differences between consecutive observations.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Differencing can help stabilize the mean of a time series by removing changes in the level of a time series, and so eliminating trends.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] This can also remove seasonality, if differences are taken appropriately (e.g. differencing observations 1 year apart to remove a yearly trend).
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Transformations such as logarithms can help to stabilize the variance of a time series.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The surrogate method for stationarization works by generating a new time series that preserves certain statistical properties of the original series while removing its nonstationary components.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] A common approach is to apply the Fourier Transform to the original time series to obtain its magnitude and phase spectra.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] The magnitude spectrum, which determines the power distribution across frequencies, is retained to preserve the global autocorrelation structure.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] Applying the inverse Fourier Transform to the modified spectra yields a strictly stationary surrogate time series: one with the same power spectrum as the original but lacking the temporal structures that caused non-stationarity.
[src:time-series-arima/stationary-process] This technique is often used in hypothesis tests for probing the stationarity property.
